[src:intersection-observer-deep/hit-testing] Hit-testing may be performed on the movement or activation of a mouse or other pointing device.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/hit-testing] Hit-testing is used by GUI environments to respond to user actions, such as selecting a menu item or a target in a game based on its visual location.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/hit-testing] In web programming languages such as HTML, SVG, and CSS, this is associated with the concept of pointer-events (e.g. user-initiated cursor movement or object selection).
[src:intersection-observer-deep/hit-testing] Collision detection is a related concept for detecting intersections of two or more different graphical objects, rather than intersection of a cursor with one or more graphical objects.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/hit-testing] There are many different algorithms that may be used to perform hit-testing, with different performance or accuracy outcomes.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/hit-testing] One common hit-test algorithm for axis aligned bounding boxes.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/hit-testing] A key idea is that the box being tested must be either entirely above, entirely below, entirely to the right or left of the current box.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/hit-testing] If this is not possible, they are colliding.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] It’s been available across browsers since March 2019.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] The Intersection Observer API provides a way to asynchronously observe changes in the intersection of a target element with an ancestor element or with a top-level document's viewport.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] Historically, detecting visibility of an element, or the relative visibility of two elements in relation to each other, has been a difficult task for which solutions have been unreliable and prone to causing the browser and the sites the user is accessing to become sluggish.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] As the web has matured, the need for this kind of information has grown.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] Implementing intersection detection in the past involved event handlers and loops calling methods like `Element.getBoundingClientRect()` to build up the needed information for every element affected.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] Since all this code runs on the main thread, even one of these can cause performance problems.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] When a site is loaded with these tests, things can get downright ugly.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] Consider a web page that uses infinite scrolling.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] It uses a vendor-provided library to manage the advertisements placed periodically throughout the page, has animated graphics here and there, and uses a custom library that draws notification boxes and the like.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] Each of these has its own intersection detection routines, all running on the main thread.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] The author of the website may not even realize this is happening, since they may know very little about the inner workings of the two libraries they are using.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] As the user scrolls the page, these intersection detection routines are firing constantly during the scroll handling code, resulting in an experience that leaves the user frustrated with the browser, the website, and their computer.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] The Intersection Observer API lets code register a callback function that is executed whenever a particular element enters or exits an intersection with another element (or the viewport), or when the intersection between two elements changes by a specified amount.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] This way, sites no longer need to do anything on the main thread to watch for this kind of element intersection, and the browser is free to optimize the management of intersections as it sees fit.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] One thing the Intersection Observer API can't do: trigger logic based on the exact number of pixels that overlap, or specifically on which ones they are.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] Typically, you'll want to watch for intersection changes with regard to the target element's closest scrollable ancestor, or, if the target element isn't a descendant of a scrollable element, the device's viewport.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] To watch for intersection relative to the device's viewport, specify `null` for the `root` option.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] Keep reading for a more detailed explanation about intersection observer options.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] Whether you're using the viewport or some other element as the root, the API works the same way, executing a callback function you provide whenever the visibility of the target element changes so that it crosses desired amounts of intersection with the root.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] The degree of intersection between the target element and its root is the **intersection ratio**.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] This is a representation of the percentage of the target element which is visible as a value between 0.0 and 1.0.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] A threshold of 1.0 means that when 100% of the target is visible within the element specified by the `root` option, the callback is invoked.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] The `options` object passed into the `IntersectionObserver()` constructor let you control the circumstances under which the observer's callback is invoked.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] The element that is used as the viewport for checking visibility of the target.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] Defaults to the browser viewport if not specified or if `null`.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] A string of one to four values similar to the CSS `margin` property, e.g., `"10px 20px 30px 40px"` (top, right, bottom, left).
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] The values can only be in pixels (`px`) or percentages (`%`).
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] This set of values serves to grow or shrink each side of the root element's bounding box before computing intersections.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] Negative values will shrink the bounding box of the root element and positive values will expand it.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] The default value, if not specified, is `"0px 0px 0px 0px"`.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] Margin around nested scroll containers that takes the same values/has same default as `rootMargin`.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] The margins are applied to nested scrollable containers before computing intersections.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] Positive values grow the clipping rectangle of the container, allowing targets to intersect before they becomes visible, while negative values shrink the clipping rectangle.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] Either a single number or an array of numbers which indicate at what percentage of the target's visibility the observer's callback should be executed.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] If you only want to detect when visibility passes the 50% mark, you can use a value of 0.5.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] If you want the callback to run every time visibility passes another 25%, you would specify the array [0, 0.25, 0.5, 0.75, 1].
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] The default is 0 (meaning the callback will be run as soon as the target element intersects or touches the boundary of the root, even if no pixels are yet visible).
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] A value of 1.0 means that the threshold isn't considered passed until every pixel is visible.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] When tracking target visibility (trackVisibility is `true`), this can be used to set the minimum delay in milliseconds between notifications from this observer.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] Limiting the notification rate is desirable because the visibility calculation is computationally intensive.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] If tracking visibility, the value will be set to 100 for any value less than 100, and you should use the largest tolerable value.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] A boolean indicating whether this `IntersectionObserver` is tracking changes in a target's visibility.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] When `false` the browser will report intersections when the target element scrolls into the root element's viewport.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] When `true`, the browser will additionally check that the target is actually visible, and hasn't been covered by other elements or potentially been distorted or hidden by a filter, reduced opacity, or some transform.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] The value is `false` by default as tracking visibility is computationally intensive.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] If this is set, a `delay` should also be set.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] The list of entries received by the callback includes one `IntersectionObserverEntry` object for each threshold-crossing event — multiple entries can be received at a time, either from multiple targets or from a single target crossing multiple thresholds in a short amount of time.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] The entries are dispatched using a queue, so they should be ordered by the time they were generated, but you should preferably use `IntersectionObserverEntry.time` to correctly order them.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] Each entry describes how much of a given element is intersecting with the root element, whether or not the element is considered to be intersecting or not, etc.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] The entry only contains information about that particular instant — if you want information that requires tracking over time, such as the scroll direction and speed, you may need to compute that yourself by memoizing previously received entries.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] Be aware that your callback is executed on the main thread.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] It should operate as quickly as possible; if anything time-consuming needs to be done, use `Window.requestIdleCallback()`.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] The code snippet below shows a callback which keeps a counter of how many times elements transition from not intersecting the root to intersecting by at least 75%.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] For a threshold value of 0.0 (default) the callback is called approximately upon transition of the boolean value of `isIntersecting`.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] The snippet thus first checks that the transition is a positive one, then determines whether `intersectionRatio` is above 75%, in which case it increments the counter.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] Whenever the target meets a threshold specified for the `IntersectionObserver`, the callback is invoked.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] Also, note that if you specified the `root` option, the target must be a descendant of the root element.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] All areas considered by the Intersection Observer API are rectangles; elements which are irregularly shaped are considered as occupying the smallest rectangle which encloses all of the element's parts.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] Similarly, if the visible portion of an element is not rectangular, the element's intersection rectangle is considered to be the smallest rectangle that contains all the visible portions of the element.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] It's useful to understand a bit about how the various properties provided by `IntersectionObserverEntry` describe an intersection.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] Before we can track the intersection of an element with a container, we need to know what that container is.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] That container is the **intersection root**, or **root element**.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] This can be either a specific element in the document which is an ancestor of the element to be observed, or `null` to use the document's viewport as the container.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] The ***root intersection rectangle*** is the rectangle used to check against the target or targets.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] The root intersection rectangle can be adjusted further by setting the **root margin**, `rootMargin`, when creating the `IntersectionObserver`.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] The values in `rootMargin` define offsets added to each side of the intersection root's bounding box to create the final intersection root bounds (which are disclosed in `IntersectionObserverEntry.rootBounds` when the callback is executed).
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] Positive values grow the box, while negative values shrink it.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] Each offset value can be only expressed in pixels (px) or a percentage (%).
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] The effect of growing the box using the root margin is to allow overflow targets to intersect with the root before they become visible.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] This can be used, for example, to start loading images just before they come into view, rather than at the point they become visible.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] In the example below, we have a scrollable box and an element that's initially out of view.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] Consider the case where you have a root element that contains nested scroll containers, and you want to observe intersections with a target inside one of those scrollable containers.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] Intersections with the target element start being observable, by default, when the target is visible within the area defined by the root; in other words, when the container is scrolled into view in the root and the target is scrolled into view within the clipping rectangle of its container.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] You can use a scroll margin to start observing intersections before or after the target is scrolled into view within its scroll container.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] The margin is added to all nested scroll containers in the root, including the root element if it is also a scroll container, and has the effect of either growing (positive margins) or shrinking (negative margin) the clipping region used for calculating intersections.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] In the example below, we have a scrollable box and an image carousel that is initially out of view.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] An observer on the root element observes the image element targets within the carousel.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] When an image element starts to intersect with the root element, the image is loaded, the intersection is logged, and the observer is removed.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] The visible images should immediately load.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] If you scroll the carousel, you should observe that the images are loaded as soon as the element becomes visible.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] After resetting the example you can use the provided control to change the scroll margin percentage.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] If you set a positive value like 20% the clip rectangle of the scroll container will be increased by 20%, and you should observe that images are detected and loaded before they come into view.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] Similarly, a negative value will mean that the intersection is detected once images are already in view.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] Rather than reporting every infinitesimal change in how much a target element is visible, the Intersection Observer API uses **thresholds**.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] When you create an observer, you can provide one or more numeric values representing percentages of the target element which are visible.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] Then, the API only reports changes to visibility which cross these thresholds.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] For example, if you want to be informed every time a target's visibility passes backward or forward through each 25% mark, you would specify the array [0, 0.25, 0.5, 0.75, 1] as the list of thresholds when creating the observer.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] When the callback is invoked, it receives a list of `IntersectionObserverEntry` objects, one for each observed target which has had the degree to which it intersects the root change such that the amount exposed crosses over one of the thresholds, in either direction.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] You can see if the target *currently* intersects the root by looking at the entry's `isIntersecting` property; if its value is `true`, the target is at least partially intersecting the root element or document.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] This lets you determine whether the entry represents a transition from the elements intersecting to no longer intersecting or a transition from not intersecting to intersecting.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] Note that it's possible to have a zero intersection rectangle, which can happen if the intersection is exactly along the boundary between the two or the area of `boundingClientRect` is zero.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] This state of the target and root sharing a boundary line is not considered enough to be considered transitioning into an intersecting state.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] To get a feeling for how thresholds work, try scrolling the box below around.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] Each colored box within it displays the percentage of itself that's visible in all four of its corners, so you can see these ratios change over time as you scroll the container.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] By default the observer provides notifications when the target element is scrolled into the root element's viewport.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] While this is all that is needed in many situations, sometimes it is important that intersections are not reported when the target has been "visually compromised".
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] For example, when measuring analytics or ad impressions, it is important that target elements are not hidden or distorted, in whole or in part.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] The `trackVisibility` setting tells the observer to only report intersections for targets that the browser does not consider to be visually compromised, such as by altering the opacity, or applying a filter or transform.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] The algorithm is conservative, and may omit elements that are technically visible, such as those with only a slight opacity reduction.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] The visibility calculation is computationally expensive and should only be used when necessary.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] When tracking visibility a `delay` should also be set to limit the minimum reporting period.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] The recommendation is that you set the delay to the largest tolerable value (the minimum delay when tracking visibility is 100 milliseconds).
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] The browser computes the final intersection rectangle as follows; this is all done for you, but it can be helpful to understand these steps in order to better grasp exactly when intersections will occur.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] Starting at the target's immediate parent block and moving outward, each containing block's clipping (if any) is applied to the intersection rectangle.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] A block's clipping is determined based on the intersection of the two blocks and the clipping mode (if any) specified by the `overflow` property.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] Setting `overflow` to anything but `visible` causes clipping to occur.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] If one of the containing elements is the root of a nested browsing context (such as the document contained in an `<iframe>`), the intersection rectangle is clipped to the containing context's viewport, and recursion upward through the containers continues with the container's containing block.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] So if the top level of an `<iframe>` is reached, the intersection rectangle is clipped to the frame's viewport, then the frame's parent element is the next block recursed through toward the intersection root.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] When recursion upward reaches the intersection root, the resulting rectangle is mapped to the intersection root's coordinate space.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] The resulting rectangle is then updated by intersecting it with the root intersection rectangle.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] This rectangle is, finally, mapped to the coordinate space of the target's `document`.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] The primary interface for the Intersection Observer API.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] Provides methods for creating and managing an observer which can watch any number of target elements for the same intersection configuration.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] Each observer can asynchronously observe changes in the intersection between one or more target elements and a shared ancestor element or with their top-level `Document`'s viewport.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] The ancestor or viewport is referred to as the **root**.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] Describes the intersection between the target element and its root container at a specific moment of transition.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] Objects of this type can only be obtained in two ways: as an input to your `IntersectionObserver` callback, or by calling `IntersectionObserver.takeRecords()`.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] This simple example causes a target element to change its color and transparency as it becomes more or less visible.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] At Timing element visibility with the Intersection Observer API, you can find a more extensive example showing how to time how long a set of elements (such as ads) are visible to the user and to react to that information by recording statistics or by updating elements.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] The HTML for this example is very short, with a primary element which is the box that we'll be targeting (with the creative ID `"box"`) and some contents within the box.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] The CSS isn't terribly important for the purposes of this example; it lays out the element and establishes that the `background-color` and `border` attributes can participate in CSS transitions, which we'll use to affect the changes to the element as it becomes more or less obscured.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] Finally, let's take a look at the JavaScript code that uses the Intersection Observer API to make things happen.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] First, we need to prepare some variables and install the observer.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] A constant which indicates how many thresholds we want to have between a visibility ratio of 0.0 and 1.0.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] This variable will be used to record what the visibility ratio was the last time a threshold was crossed; this will let us figure out whether the target element is becoming more or less visible.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] A string defining a color we'll apply to the target element when the visibility ratio is increasing.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] The word "ratio" in this string will be replaced with the target's current visibility ratio, so that the element not only changes color but also becomes increasingly opaque as it becomes less obscured.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] Similarly, this is a string defining a color we'll apply when the visibility ratio is decreasing.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] We get a reference to the element with the ID `"box"` using `querySelector()`, then call the `createObserver()` method we'll create in a moment to handle building and installing the intersection observer.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] The `createObserver()` method is called once page load is complete to handle actually creating the new `IntersectionObserver` and starting the process of observing the target element.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] This begins by setting up an `options` object containing the settings for the observer.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] We want to watch for changes in visibility of the target element relative to the document's viewport, so `root` is `null`.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] We need no margin, so the margin offset, `rootMargin`, is specified as "0px".
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] This causes the observer to watch for changes in the intersection between the target element's bounds and those of the viewport, without any added (or subtracted) space.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] The list of visibility ratio thresholds, `threshold`, is constructed by the function `buildThresholdList()`.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] The threshold list is built programmatically in this example since there are a number of them and the number is intended to be adjustable.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] Once `options` is ready, we create the new observer, calling the `IntersectionObserver()` constructor, specifying a function to be called when intersection crosses one of our thresholds, `handleIntersect()`, and our set of options.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] We then call `observe()` on the returned observer, passing into it the desired target element.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] We could opt to monitor multiple elements for visibility intersection changes with respect to the viewport by calling `observer.observe()` for each of those elements, if we wanted to do so.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] This builds the array of thresholds—each of which is a ratio between 0.0 and 1.0, by pushing the value `i/numSteps` onto the `thresholds` array for each integer `i` between 1 and `numSteps`.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] We could, of course, hard-code the array of thresholds into our code, and often that's what you'll end up doing.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] But this example leaves room for adding configuration controls to adjust the granularity, for example.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] The result: not only does the color get changed, but the transparency of the target element changes, too; as the intersection ratio goes down, the background color's alpha value goes down with it, resulting in an element that's more transparent.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] Similarly, if the `intersectionRatio` is going down, we use the string `decreasingColor` and replace the word "ratio" in that with the `intersectionRatio` before setting the target element's `background-color`.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] Finally, in order to track whether the intersection ratio is going up or down, we remember the current ratio in the variable `prevRatio`.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] Scroll this page up and down and notice how the appearance of the box changes as you do so.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersection-observer-api] There's an even more extensive example at Timing element visibility with the Intersection Observer API.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserver-rootmargin] The **`rootMargin`** read-only property of the `IntersectionObserver` interface is a string with syntax similar to that of the CSS `margin` property.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserver-rootmargin] Each side of the rectangle represented by `rootMargin` is added to the corresponding side in the `root` element's bounding box before the intersection test is performed.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserver-rootmargin] This lets you, for example, adjust the bounds outward so that the target element is considered 100% visible even if a certain number of pixels worth of width or height is clipped away, or treat the target as partially hidden if an edge is too close to the edge of the root's bounding box.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserver-rootmargin] See how intersections are calculated for a more in-depth look at the root margin and how it works with the root's bounding box.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserver-rootmargin] A string, formatted similarly to the CSS `margin` property's value, which contains offsets for one or more sides of the root's bounding box.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserver-rootmargin] These offsets are added to the corresponding values in the root's bounding box before the intersection between the resulting rectangle and the target element's bounds.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserver-rootmargin] The string returned by this property may not match the one specified when the `IntersectionObserver` was instantiated.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserver-rootmargin] For example, the result always contains four components, though the input may have fewer.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserver-rootmargin] If `rootMargin` isn't specified when the object was instantiated, it defaults to the string `"0px 0px 0px 0px"`, meaning that the intersection will be computed between the root element's unmodified bounds rectangle and the target's bounds.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserver-rootmargin] How intersections are calculated describes how the `rootMargin` is used in more detail.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserver-thresholds] The **`thresholds`** read-only property of the `IntersectionObserver` interface returns the list of intersection thresholds that was specified when the observer was instantiated with `IntersectionObserver()`.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserver-thresholds] If only one threshold ratio was provided when instantiating the object, this will be an array containing that single value.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserver-thresholds] See the Intersection Observer page to learn how thresholds work.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserver-thresholds] An array of intersection thresholds, originally specified using the `threshold` property when instantiating the observer.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserver-thresholds] If only one observer was specified, without being in an array, this value is a one-entry array containing that threshold.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserver-thresholds] Regardless of the order your original `threshold` array was in, this one is always sorted in numerically increasing order.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserver-thresholds] If no `threshold` option was included when `IntersectionObserver()` was used to instantiate the observer, the value of `thresholds` is `[0]`.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserver] The **`IntersectionObserver`** interface of the Intersection Observer API provides a way to asynchronously observe changes in the intersection of a target element with an ancestor element or with a top-level document's viewport.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserver] The ancestor element or viewport is referred to as the root.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserver] When an `IntersectionObserver` is created, it's configured to watch for given ratios of visibility within the root.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserver] The configuration cannot be changed once the `IntersectionObserver` is created, so a given observer object is only useful for watching for specific changes in degree of visibility; however, you can watch multiple target elements with the same observer.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserver] Creates a new `IntersectionObserver` object which will execute a specified callback function when it detects that a target element's visibility has crossed one or more thresholds.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserver] An integer indicating the minimum delay between notifications from this observer.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserver] The `Element` or `Document` whose bounds are used as the bounding box when testing for intersection.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserver] If no `root` value was passed to the constructor or its value is `null`, the top-level document's viewport is used.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserver] An offset rectangle applied to the root's bounding box when calculating intersections, effectively shrinking or growing the root for calculation purposes.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserver] The value returned by this property may not be the same as the one specified when calling the constructor as it may be changed to match internal requirements.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserver] Each offset can be expressed in pixels (`px`) or percentages (`%`).
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserver] An offset rectangle applied to each scroll container on the path from intersection root to target, effectively shrinking or growing the clip rectangles used to calculate intersections.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserver] The value returned by this property may not be the same as the one specified when calling the constructor.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserver] A list of thresholds, sorted in increasing numeric order, where each threshold is a ratio of intersection area to bounding box area of an observed target.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserver] Notifications for a target are generated when any of the thresholds are crossed for that target.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserver] If no value was passed to the constructor, 0 is used.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserver] A boolean indicating whether this `IntersectionObserver` is checking that the target does not have compromised visibility.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserver] Stops the `IntersectionObserver` object from observing any target.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserver] Tells the `IntersectionObserver` a target element to observe.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserver] Returns an array of `IntersectionObserverEntry` objects for all observed targets.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserver] Tells the `IntersectionObserver` to stop observing a particular target element.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserverentry] The **`IntersectionObserverEntry`** interface of the Intersection Observer API describes the intersection between the target element and its root container at a specific moment of transition.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserverentry] Instances of `IntersectionObserverEntry` are delivered to an `IntersectionObserver` callback in its `entries` parameter; otherwise, these objects can only be obtained by calling `IntersectionObserver.takeRecords()`.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserverentry] Creates a new `IntersectionObserverEntry` object.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserverentry] Returns the bounds rectangle of the target element as a `DOMRectReadOnly`.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserverentry] The bounds are computed as described in the documentation for `Element.getBoundingClientRect()`.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserverentry] Returns the ratio of the `intersectionRect` to the `boundingClientRect`.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserverentry] Returns a `DOMRectReadOnly` representing the target's visible area.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserverentry] A Boolean value which is `true` if the target element intersects with the intersection observer's root.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserverentry] If this is `true`, then, the `IntersectionObserverEntry` describes a transition into a state of intersection; if it's `false`, then you know the transition is from intersecting to not-intersecting.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserverentry] Returns a `DOMRectReadOnly` for the intersection observer's root.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserverentry] The `Element` whose intersection with the root changed.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/intersectionobserverentry] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` indicating the time at which the intersection was recorded, relative to the `IntersectionObserver`'s time origin.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/viewport] A **viewport** is a polygon viewing region in computer graphics.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/viewport] In computer graphics theory, there are two region-like notions of relevance when rendering some objects to an image.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/viewport] In textbook terminology, the *world coordinate window* is the area of interest (meaning what the user wants to visualize) in some application-specific coordinates, e.g. miles, centimeters etc.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/viewport] The word *window* as used here should not be confused with the GUI window, i.e. the notion used in window managers.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/viewport] Rather it is an analogy with how a window limits what one can see outside a room.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/viewport] In contrast, the *viewport* is an area (typically rectangular) expressed in rendering-device-specific coordinates, e.g. pixels for screen coordinates, in which the objects of interest are going to be rendered.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/viewport] Clipping to the world-coordinates window is usually applied to the objects before they are passed through the window-to-viewport transformation.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/viewport] For a 2D object, the latter transformation is simply a combination of translation and scaling, the latter not necessarily uniform.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/viewport] An analogy of this transformation process based on traditional photography notions is to equate the world-clipping window with the camera settings and the variously sized prints that can be obtained from the resulting film image as possible viewports.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/viewport] In 3D computer graphics, the viewport refers to the 2D rectangle used to project the 3D scene to the position of a virtual camera.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/viewport] A viewport is a region of the screen used to display a portion of the total image to be shown.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/viewport] In virtual desktops, the viewport is the visible portion of a 2D area which is larger than the visualization device.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/viewport] When viewing a document in a web browser, the viewport is the region of the browser window which contains the visible portion of the document.
[src:intersection-observer-deep/viewport] If the size of the viewport changes, for example as a result of the user resizing the browser window, then the browser may reflow the document (recalculate the locations and sizes of elements of the document).
[src:intersection-observer-deep/viewport] If the document is larger than the viewport, the user can control the portion of the document which is visible by scrolling in the viewport.
